      "assistant_content": "Here's a Python script that checks the weather using an API:\n\n```python\nimport requests\n\ndef get_weather(city, api_key):\n    \"\"\"Fetch weather data for a given city.\"\"\"\n    url = \"https://api.openweathermap.org/data/2.5/weather\"\n    params = {\n        'q': city,\n        'appid': api_key,\n        'units': 'metric'\n    }\n    \n    try:\n        response = requests.get(url, params=params)\n        response.raise_for_status()\n        data = response.json()\n        \n        return {\n            'city': data['name'],\n            'temperature': data['main']['temp'],\n            'description': data['weather'][0]['description'],\n            'humidity': data['main']['humidity']\n        }\n    except requests.exceptions.RequestException as e:\n        return {'error': str(e)}\n\n# Example usage\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    API_KEY = \"your_api_key_here\"  # Get from https://openweathermap.org/api\n    city = \"London\"\n    \n    weather = get_weather(city, API_KEY)\n    \n    if 'error' in weather:\n        print(f\"Error: {weather['error']}\")\n    else:\n        print(f\"Weather in {weather['city']}:\")\n        print(f\"Temperature: {weather['temperature']}°C\")\n        print(f\"Condition: {weather['description']}\")\n        print(f\"Humidity: {weather['humidity']}%\")\n```\n\n**Requirements:**\n- Install requests: `pip install requests`\n- Get a free API key from [OpenWeatherMap](https://openweathermap.org/api)\n\n**Note:** Replace `\"your_api_key_here\"` with your actual API key. The script uses metric units (Celsius). You can change to imperial by setting `'units': 'imperial'`.",
